{
  "topicId": "m6-t1",
  "title": "Asking about Directions",
  "dialect": "levantine",
  "steps": [
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Starting Politely: 'Excuse Me'"
        },
        "text": "To ask for directions, it's polite to start with 'Excuse me'. The phrase changes slightly depending on whether you're speaking to a male or a female. Pay attention to the diacritical marks on the last letter for pronunciation.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "لو سمحتَ",
            "english": "Excuse me (to a male)",
            "transliteration": "Law samaḥta",
            "diacriticalNotes": "The 'ت' has a fatḥa (َ) for male."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "لو سمحتِ",
            "english": "Excuse me (to a female)",
            "transliteration": "Law samaḥti",
            "diacriticalNotes": "The 'ت' has a kasra (ِ) for female."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Asking 'Where is...?'"
        },
        "text": "After a polite opening, you can ask 'Where is...?' using 'وين الـ...؟' This is a very common and versatile phrase in Levantine Arabic.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "وين الـ...؟",
            "english": "Where is the...?",
            "transliteration": "Wayn il-...?"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "وين المطعم؟",
            "english": "Where is the restaurant?",
            "transliteration": "Wayn il-maṭʕam?"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Common Places/Landmarks (Part 1)"
        },
